## Summary
This is an article about how our stories about the world define our perception of the world, and how that perception defines our politics, and how our politics come back to define our realities. A bad story, then, is often the catalyst of bad external outcomes. I propose that we pay better attention to, and mend our stories to mend our world. I illustrate this with two competing narratives, the bastardization of Darwin's evolutionary theory--Social Darwinism and Kropotkin's correction of it in mutual aid. I illustrate my point concerning how bad stories lead to bad outcomes by showing how each of these stories led to their bad outcomes.

I conclude by asking, which stories do we tell ourselves now and how do they impact us and our world?

