## Perception is Reality is Perception

As human beings, stories are how we make sense of the world. When we are confronted with facts about "the world", from the limitlessness of the cosmos to our worth as human beings, we interpret them and form it into a coherent story.

We do not do this alone. As a society, we often need to agree on our understanding of those hard facts to properly collaborate. Those stories, then, transcend the individual as we share them with others. We share our ways of understanding the world with other people, be it through poetry, art, philosophy or mathematics. Those stories, in turn, affect how we interpret other facts going forward. Stories are social infrastructure for making sense of the world.

Every mathematical theory, every fashion piece, every essay publication, every hearth song, contains within it a way of interpreting the world.

## The power of a story

After the world has been interpreted for us to understand, we then go forward and act on it. Humans take actions in the world based on our understanding of it. It is because of this that I believe that stories are one of the most powerful aspects of human society. How we operate our societies, how we view and treat each other, the values we elevate and the ills that come of them, it all comes down to our stories.

## Oh, but won't you tell me a story?

It is my belief that the most important aspects of our society is not
our technology, even though admittedly we live in a technological
society, but our stories. The truths we whisper to each other under
moonlight or beam directly to our brains through brightly-lit LED screens.

As an African, a descendant of an oral culture, stories are my
existence. I know just how important they can be. I have seen them used to communicate really strong ideas in just a few sentences, and I've seen them used to shut down further thought. 

Stories are the roads on which we tread towards the future. They are the lens with which we view the past.
Stories are the hands we use to curb the worrying expanse of infinitude.

Stories are a double-edged sword.

What is culture but a story we tell each other about who we are? A story that sets our expectation of reality without actually definitely defining it. But if the stories we tell ourselves set our expectations of reality, then they also--by choosing what aspects of the story get emphasized and what doesn't--very subtly exclude other interpretations of reality.

David Forster-Wallace puts it better:

>There are these two guys sitting together in a bar in the remote Alaskan wilderness. One of the guys is religious, the other is an atheist, and the two are arguing about the existence of God with that special intensity that comes after about the fourth beer.
>
>The atheist says: “Look, it’s not like I don’t have actual reasons for not believing in God. It’s not like I haven’t ever experimented with the whole God and prayer thing. Just last month I got caught away from the camp in that terrible blizzard, and I was totally lost and I couldn’t see a thing, and it was 50 below, and so I tried it: I fell to my knees in the snow and cried out ‘Oh, God, if there is a God, I’m lost in this blizzard, and I’m gonna die if you don’t help me.’” And now, in the bar, the religious guy looks at the atheist all puzzled. “Well then you must believe now,” he says, “After all, here you are, alive.” The atheist just rolls his eyes. “No, man, all that was was a couple Eskimos happened to come wandering by and showed me the way back to camp.”
>
>*- [This Is Water: Some Thoughts, Delivered on a Significant Occasion,
>about Living a Compassionate Life, David Forster Wallace](https://fs.blog/david-foster-wallace-this-is-water/)*

Now. Depending on who you are, something inside you has already passed judgment concerning who was Right in the above discussion, perhaps their story aligns with yours a bit better. It is not my place to tell you who was right in the story, and frankly I don't care that much. I would say though, maybe examine why you think one of them was right a bit longer.

Crucially, I want you to notice something. Both men do not disagree on the facts, they disagree on the interpretation of those facts. The stories that they use to interprete reality give them different lenses upon which to view the very same subject. It's a fascinating thing.

## What the hell is water?

The reason I think our stories are important is that they channel us through a particular line of thinking. They make it difficult to think outside of their construct, and when they are powerful enough, they make it seem like there's no other way to think. Once they get to that point, they become intangible but ever-present. They disappear, not because they aren't there, but because they are always there. Kind of like air. Or water:

>There are these two young fish swimming along and they happen to meet an older fish swimming the other way, who nods at them and says “Morning, boys. How’s the water?” And the two young fish swim on for a bit, and then eventually one of them looks over at the other and goes “What the hell is water?”"
>
>*- [This Is Water: Some Thoughts, Delivered on a Significant Occasion,
>about Living a Compassionate Life, David Forster Wallace](https://fs.blog/david-foster-wallace-this-is-water/)*

Like water for fish, or air for humans, a story can surround you so completely that it disappears into significance. It becomes truth.

## With Verity I say unto you, "Once upon a time"

