>but mine is, 'the stories you tell come true.' If you believe everyone
>is untrustworthy, you'll build that into your systems so that even the
>best people have to act like the worst people to get anything done. If
>you assume people are okay, you live a much happier life.”
>
> *- Walkaway, Cory Doctorow*

So, if I am right that the stories we tell ourselves get elevated unto the status of "reality" itself, then maybe we should take a closer look at these stories. Let's look at their effects, let's look at how they create characters and assume motivations.

Let's take a simple example of one of our core stories in our society, the popular story that is based on a complete distortion of Darwin's work on evolution: the story of The Survival of The Fittest.

When Darwin wrote *On The Origin of Species, by means of Natural Selection*, the foremost idea was the Natural Selection part. Perhaps, it requires some explanation. Natural Selection is the process by which organisms that possess attributes that **best fit** their environment reproduce. Over time, this leads to those attributes dominating over unfit attributes.

To ground this in its historical context, many natural historians (we would call them biologists now) thought that individual species were created, not evolved. Incidentally, many people I know still hold this view. Although Darwin wasn't the first person to have the idea that perhaps species change, he was the one that fleshed out how that happens and provided evidence to support the view.

Yet.

The popular understanding of Darwin's work on evolution is that the "strongest" survive. Somehow, the word fittest gets conflated with the word "strongest". Perhaps, that's because fit also means strong, but this also happens to people who should know better. There's a whole strain of Darwinist thought called Social Darwinism that interprets and develops Darwin's work this way:

>Social Darwinists believe that the strong should see their wealth and power increase,
>while the weak should see their wealth and power decrease.
>
> *- [Wikipedia: Social Darwinism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Darwinism)*

They developed this even more to claim that social interventions that interfered with the processes of "natural selection" were wrong and disrupting "Nature". So, when there's economic inequality, well, that's just natural selection at work.

You see, to these people, Nature---this amorphous and amoral entity---was doing the supposedly Divine work of dividing humans (and all other organisms) into **inferiors** and **superiors**. To interfere with that was a dangerous and burdensome thing.

>In Galton's view, social institutions such as welfare and insane asylums were allowing **inferior humans** to survive and reproduce at levels faster than the more **"superior" humans** in respectable society, and if corrections were not soon taken, society would be awash with "inferiors".
>
> *- [Wikipedia: Social Darwinism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Darwinism)*

Who were the inferiors and who were the superiors? Well, it depends. Some social darwinists used this line of thinking to justify colonialism, imperialism, racism and many other social ills.

>[Herbert Spencer] believed that biological evolution had brought about human intellect, which in turn produced society. Therefore, he argued, human intellect and social activities were products of biological evolution, and all three operated on natural laws. 
>...
>He asserted that all aspects of life, be it human, plant, or animal life, were guided by the constant struggle in which the weak were subjugated by the strong. However undesirable humanitarians might find this process, he argued, it was the natural order of things and could not be altered by charity, welfare policies, or legislative actions.
> *- [Encyclopedia.com: Social Darwinism Emerges and Is Used to Justify Imperialism, Racism, and Conservative Economic and Social Policies ](https://www.encyclopedia.com/science/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/social-darwinism-emerges-and-used-justify-imperialism-racism-and-conservative-economic-and-social "Talking specifically about Herbert Spencer, one of the the earliest Social Darwinists")*

This sort of story then leads to a conservatism---a preservation of how things are, regardless of how bad they are or who they hurt. As a side note, It's pretty convenient for him to have said this as an educated, rich, white man. He wasn't one of the people subjugated by the socio-economic systems that he preserved. Would he still have held the same views if he was amongst the poorest in his society? Would he have held the same views if he was found on the other end of pseudo-science claiming that he was "inferior" and therefore unworthy of consideration and solidarity?

>The simpler aspects of Social Darwinism followed the earlier Malthusian ideas that humans, especially males, require competition in their lives to survive. Further, the poor should have to provide for themselves and not be given any aid.
>
> *- [Wikipedia: Social Darwinism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Darwinism)*

These stories were influential in their time. They were used to push all sort of nefarious agendas, from aggressive laissez-faire capitalism to colonialism. They are still present in our time too, although much less pronounced.

The culmination of Social Darwinism was Hitler and his eugenicist war. After the second world war, the Social Darwinism fell out of favour because it was seen as the very same theories that were used by *the enemy* to justify their atrocities.

I want to explore a different story.

## You scratch my back, I scratch yours

Pyotr Kropotkin was a Russian philosopher and geographer, who, upon reading Darwin--and considering the bastardization of his work--was dissatisfied. In response--not to Darwin per se, but to the social darwinists--he wrote *Mutual Aid: A factor of Evolution*.

The core thesis of the book is simple: Darwin's *On The Origin of Species* clearly listed out arguments for Natural Selection as a factor of evolution, as well as mutual struggle (the struggle of all against all), but that wasn't the only factor of evolution. Mutual Aid--that is, **cooperation**, was just as much, if not more of a factor. Mutual Aid, to Kropotkin, was a more convincing reason for animals to develop progressive capaciticies (to evolve). He saw that we all struggle against the pressures of the environment: sickness, sadness, isolation, poverty; yet, the animals (and people) who came out of those conditions stronger were often the more sociable and collaborative ones, not the aggressively competitive ones.

Based on this, Kropotkin created his own political theories based on mutual aid and voluntary association. While the social darwinists were trying to provide "scientific" proof against altruism, social interventions into societal ills, Darwin provided actual scientific proof for altruism and love. He wrote a different story, and we are all the better for it.

To be clear, Kropotkin did not think that mutual struggle (the fight of all against all) did not exist, but instead he saw that Mutual Aid was more prevalent and more important; and more admirable. 

## So, what's the moral?

The point of this--the point of all of this--is how we look at each other. Humans are a social species, and that is not by accident. I promised you some altruism and activism, and I'm about to deliver. I think that the world has overindexed on the first story. We conceive as ourselves only as competitors to ourselves. I do not believe that human beings will survive much longer on this earth if we do not see ourselves as comrades but instead as opponents and enemies.

And. And, it all starts with the stories we tell each other about ourselves.
